<div id="review_3814532585" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3814532585" />
    <a title="Grymm Gevierre" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/110261611-grymm-gevierre"><img alt="Grymm Gevierre" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1616326387p2/110261611.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3814532585?book_show_action=true">Feb 02, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Grymm Gevierre" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Grymm Gevierre" href="/user/show/110261611-grymm-gevierre">Grymm Gevierre</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3814532585" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11913970344112864902"> I’ve gone through a lot of self-help books over the past 5 or so years. I would have never given a single one a chance if it weren’t for Mark Manson, but here we are, a genre I found I actually enjoy reading about. Many of them take a very similar approach, but each one has something that stands out. <br/> What’s neat about Gill’s book is that the book doesn’t focus on motivation for the sake of productivity, impact on others, or becoming the optimal self. Instead Gill focuses on the content (or som</span>
  <span id="freeText11913970344112864902" style="display:none"> I’ve gone through a lot of self-help books over the past 5 or so years. I would have never given a single one a chance if it weren’t for Mark Manson, but here we are, a genre I found I actually enjoy reading about. Many of them take a very similar approach, but each one has something that stands out. <br /> What’s neat about Gill’s book is that the book doesn’t focus on motivation for the sake of productivity, impact on others, or becoming the optimal self. Instead Gill focuses on the content (or sometimes depressing) aspects that bring us down for reasons that are sometimes out of our grasps. The focus here, no matter what the outcome, is self and happiness, not achievements and productivity. <br /> This book comes off as a help book, but really it’s a commentary on society and how our rapid-progression in tech to normalize and bring us together has really done quite the opposite. It also doesn’t shy away from being altruistic to feel good for yourself, which is something a lot of people avoid outright saying. <br /> Overall, it is a clever and unique (not original, but done in an original way) take on self-care and happiness. It’s definitely up there on my list of self-help books. <br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11913970344112864902" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


